{
    "analysis": "The last Executor run performed a metric-level anomaly scan for allowed root-cause components and returned that almost every (component, KPI) pair shows anomalies in-window. However many series are constant (global_p95 == global_p5 and max == min), which makes the simple >=P95 or <=P5 rule produce many false positives. From earlier summaries we observed concentrated error log activity on apache frontends around 1615559702–1615559770 (2021-03-12T22:35:02 to 22:36:10+08) and IG traces (IG01, IG02) showing large trace.self.duration_p95 (~60s) and high row_count, and Tomcat01 having many request-related KPIs with high p95. These point to a likely performance/failure window around ~22:35+08:00 involving the ingress (IG01/IG02) and downstream Tomcat(s). To narrow the root cause we must now run a focused trace-level anomaly detection (using proper global thresholds computed from full trace series) and identify which trace series have true spikes within the incident window (not constant-valued noise). Traces are also useful to find the most-downstream faulty service when multiple service-level faults exist.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the kernel-stored trace table, perform a trace-level threshold calculation and anomaly scan limited to allowed root-cause components [\"apache01\",\"apache02\",\"Tomcat01\",\"Tomcat02\",\"Tomcat03\",\"Tomcat04\",\"MG01\",\"MG02\",\"IG01\",\"IG02\",\"Mysql01\",\"Mysql02\",\"Redis01\",\"Redis02\"]: \n1) For each (cmdb_id,trace_name) pair present in trace.csv, compute global_p95 and global_p5 of value using the full available series (do NOT filter by incident window for threshold calculation). Store these in kernel variables.\n2) Filter trace.csv to the incident window: timestamps >= 1615559400 and <= 1615561200.\n3) For each (cmdb_id,trace_name) pair, compute: points_in_window (count), anomalies_above_p95 (count of value >= global_p95), anomalies_below_p5 (count of value <= global_p5), anomalies_total (sum of the two), earliest_anom_ts (minimum timestamp among anomaly points; NULL if none), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, and global_p95, global_p5.\n4) Return a compact table of up to top 20 rows sorted by anomalies_total descending, with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_p95, global_p5, points_in_window, anomalies_above_p95, anomalies_below_p5, anomalies_total, earliest_anom_ts, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window. Also return the total number of (cmdb_id,trace_name) pairs scanned and the number of pairs that had anomalies_total >= 1. Keep output textual and bounded to top 20 rows."
}

